text:
Honestly, I don't really care for that sort of thing in the first place. I get that some people like mastering a skill-based game and that there's a performative side to it, but at some point it just starts to look like bragging.

I get a bit annoyed whenever I try to look up a boss fight and only find those "I beat this super-hard boss in record time without being hit even once" type videos, because I kinda want to see what the fight is like for a normal person and maybe get a look what sort of cool moves the boss brings to it.

(Kingdom Hearts players, I'm looking at you.)
author: @RelativelyBest

text: I think a lot of people don't realise that these games were designed to be replayed. That's why the combat system is so flexible with such a low skill floor and high skill ceiling. Nobody was expected to master the combat system in these games throughout their first casual playthrough. You're meant to just have fun playing it the way it is most comfortable for you. Once you've had your casual fun and want more, you can start practicing the more advanced stuff.

text:
So, a couple of things about the Agnus/DT segment.

1. It's so weird to think that someone as scummy as Agnus could spawn someone as cool as Nico, but them's the brakes.
2. I love how Nero's DT in 5 is based on the DT Stand he gets in this game.
3. Nero restoring the Yamato is obviously supposed to be the big hint that he's connected to Vergil, but I love how "Power... Give me more power" indicates that Vergil's lust for power is genetic. MOTIVATION is in the bloodstream!

We also see a bit of those genetics in 5, before the Artemis fight. Nero says something like “Without strength, you can’t protect anyone... I know that.” So even though he doesn’t know Vergil exists at this point, he still knows Vergil’s philosophy. But instead of interpreting that quote as needing the power to protect himself, Nero interprets it as needing to be strong enough to protect the people he cares about.
